# TypeScript And Data Services

- Keep TypeScript strict: avoid `any`, preserve discriminated unions/enums, and prefer explicit return types for exported utilities and services.
- Model shared data in `src/types` and import those types rather than duplicating shapes in components or tests.
- Put Firebase reads/writes in `src/services`, not components. Components should call service functions or hooks and handle UI state.
- Validate required auth and user identifiers before writes. Prefer the authenticated Firebase uid over caller-provided user ids for persisted user data.
- Preserve Firestore collection conventions, including user subcollections and documented legacy fallback reads where they still protect existing data.
- Remove `undefined` fields before writing nested objects to Firestore. Keep `null` only when it is an intentional stored value.
- Use local-date helpers from `src/utils/dateUtils` for day keys and week ranges. Do not use `toISOString()` for user-facing `YYYY-MM-DD` keys.
- For exercise/activity logic, use existing resolvers and helpers such as activity type resolution, session tracking, superset utilities, and volume/date utilities.
- Keep pure calculations separate from async service calls when possible so they can be unit tested without Firebase.
- Handle permission-denied and missing-index Firebase errors deliberately. Return safe empty results only where the surrounding feature already expects that behavior.
